div.p:
There are of course existing strategies for ensuring the long-time accessibility of living resources: 
                    (1) investing sufficient money and human resources (Smithies et al. 2019) for data centers, libraries and infrastructures that support researchers with RDM and that offer technical solutions for storing research results and hosting living resources; 
                    (2) restricting technology-stacks (Arneil et al. 2019) for developing living resources, ideally on the basis of community-driven de-facto standards (see the discussion in Cugliana and van Zundert 2022: p. 49-50), but also on the basis of competencies and infrastructural facilities offered by data centers, libraries and infrastructural institutions; 
                    (3) virtualization (Smithies et al. 2019) through technologies such as Docker; and 
                    (4) static hosting of living resources (Arneil et al. 2019) e.g., an HTML version of a resource can reduce the maintenance effort for data centers, libraries and infrastructural institutions as well as for the researchers themselves and allowing easier hosting of multiple living resources.
